{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637332"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:41:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:41:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17650"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17650"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75454"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10364"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60964"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7829"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24241"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75454"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA randomised controlled trial comparing two pain medications enrolled 5,000 participants. The study found that medication A reduced average pain scores by 0.3 points on a 10-point scale compared to medication B (P = 0.02).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the interpretation of these results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The large sample size increases the clinical importance of the finding","The difference is statistically significant but not clinically meaningful","The difference between medications is both statistically and clinically significant","The P-value proves medication A is superior to medication B","The difference is clinically meaningful but not statistically significant"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis example demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Estatistical significance without clinical meaningfulness\u003C/strong\u003E. While the P-value of 0.02 indicates statistical significance (P \u003C 0.05), a difference of 0.3 points on a 10-point pain scale is too small to be clinically relevant for patients. Note that this finding of clinical insignificance has occurred despite a reasonable sample size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis illustrates an important principle in clinical research - statistical significance (P \u003C 0.05) does not automatically equate to clinical importance. The magnitude of effect must be large enough to be meaningful for patient care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A P-value less than 0.05 indicates statistical significance but does not necessarily imply clinical importance.","Clinical significance depends on the magnitude of effect and its practical relevance to patient care.","Large sample sizes can detect very small differences that are statistically significant but clinically meaningless."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60964"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17650"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60964"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T20:38:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T20:38:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"